4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Public, nonprofit hospitals and health care
6 facilities may be operated by regional health care
7 authorities that are created pursuant to the "Health
8 Care Authorities Act of 1982." The Health Care
9 Authorities Act allows the creation of a new health
10 care authority that is derived from an existing health
11 care authority, but does not specify any procedural
12 steps for taking this action.
13 This bill would allow a county or municipality
14 to approve the incorporation of a new health care
15 authority to serve an area that is already within an
16 existing health care authority. Other counties or
17 municipalities in the existing health care authority
18 would be required to cooperate with the separation of a
19 new health care authority from the existing authority.
20 This bill would require the boards of directors
21 of the original health care authority and the
22 newly-established health care authority to negotiate a
23 plan of separation to operate their respective health
24 care authorities, including the transfer of health care
25 facilities to the new authority and a fair division of
26 existing liabilities and assets.
27 If the two authorities are unable to reach a
28 separation agreement, this bill further provides for
Page 1

separation agreement, this bill further provides for
SB352 INTRODUCED
29 binding arbitration to achieve an agreement under the
30 jurisdiction of the judge of probate.
