34 A BILL
35 TO BE ENTITLED
36 AN ACT
37
38 Relating to health care authorities; to add Section
39 22-21-340.1 to the Code of Alabama 1975, to further provide
40 for health care authorities by establishing a procedure by
41 which a new health care authority may be incorporated and
42 established from an existing health care authority; to provide
43 for a plan for distribution of assets and liabilities between
44 an existing health care authority and a new health care
45 authority; and to provide for settlement by arbitration.
46 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
47 Section 1. Section 22-21-340.1 is added to the Code of
48 Alabama 1975:
49 §22-21-340.1
50 (a)(1) Pursuant to Section 22-21-340, a governing body
51 of a political subdivision that has authorized, or that is
52 located within the service area of, an existing authority, may
53 authorize the incorporation of a new authority that is
54 intended to encompass part of the service area of the existing
55 authority upon application made to the governing body
56 according to the requirements of Section 22-21-313.
Page 2

according to the requirements of Section 22-21-313.
SB352 INTRODUCED
57 (2) In a resolution authorizing the incorporation of a
58 new authority pursuant to Section 22-21-313(b), the governing
59 body of the authorizing subdivision shall include, as part of
60 the determination that it is wise, expedient, and necessary
61 that a new authority be incorporated, as many of the following
62 reasons as may apply:
63 a. In the absence of a separate authority, the
64 financial viability and survival of existing health care
65 facilities is in doubt.
66 b. The geographic area proposed to be served by the new
67 authority may receive more efficient or accessible health care
68 services and infrastructure than is currently the case under
69 the existing authority.
70 c. Conflicts concerning priorities in health care
71 delivery, planning, budgeting, revenue, or allocation of
72 resources exist between the board of directors or a governing
73 body of other authorizing subdivisions of the existing
74 authority, and the authorizing subdivision or individuals
75 involved in governance or operation of a health care facility
76 located in the proposed service area of the new authority,
77 which, after good faith efforts, cannot be satisfactorily
78 resolved in the existing authority.
79 (3)a. Upon authorization of the incorporation of a new
80 authority under subdivision (1), the applicants shall file a
81 certificate of incorporation for the new authority according
82 to, and in conformity with, the requirements of Section
83 22-21-314. The certificate of incorporation shall include a
84 description of the existing health care facilities and other
Page 3

description of the existing health care facilities and other
SB352 INTRODUCED
85 assets that the new authority intends to acquire and operate
86 from the existing authority.
87 b. The board of directors of the new authority shall be
88 comprised of members who do not currently serve on the board
89 of directors of the existing authority, and shall otherwise be
90 appointed in accordance with Section 22-21-316(a), including
91 the requirement that a majority of members be chosen by the
92 governing body of the authorizing subdivision.
93 (b)(1) The incorporators of the new authority shall
94 serve by certified U.S. mail, return receipt requested, a copy
95 of the certificate of incorporation to all of the following:
96 a. The governing body of each authorizing subdivision
97 of the existing authority.
98 b. The board of directors of the existing authority.
99 c. The board of directors of each health care facility
100 or hospital corporation located within the service area of the
101 existing authority.
102 (2) Upon receipt by the parties listed in subdivision
103 (1) of the certificate of incorporation of the new authority,
104 all of the following actions shall occur:
105 a. The board of the existing authority, pursuant to
106 Section 22-21-315, shall amend the certificate of
107 incorporation to reflect that the service area shall no longer
108 encompass the service area of the new authority. In so doing,
109 the board may change the name of the existing authority
110 pursuant to Section 22-21-314(b)(2) to more accurately reflect
111 the reduction in area of the existing authority.
112 b. The authorizing subdivisions of the existing
Page 4

b. The authorizing subdivisions of the existing
SB352 INTRODUCED
113 authority shall, by resolution, approve the amendment required
114 in paragraph a. according to the procedure provided in Section
115 22-21-315(b).
116 (3) No more than 10 days after the filing and recording
117 of the amended certificate of incorporation for the existing
118 authority in the office of the Judge of Probate as required by
119 Section 22-21-315(c), the Judge of Probate shall enter an
120 order that contains all of the following:
121 a. Directs the board of directors of the existing
122 authority and the board of directors of the new authority to
123 commence development of the plan required by subsection (c),
124 to be finalized in no more than 12 months from the date of
125 entry of the order.
126 b. Directs the board of directors of the existing
127 authority and the board of directors of the new authority to
128 report periodically to the Judge of Probate on the status of
129 the plan development required by subsection (c), on no less
130 than a quarterly basis. Each report shall summarize in writing
131 the matters upon which the two boards have reached agreement
132 and the matters upon which agreement has not been attained.
133 (c)(1) The board of directors of the existing authority
134 shall promptly negotiate in good faith with the board of
135 directors of the new authority to develop a plan for the
136 separation, governance, and operation of the two authorities
137 which shall address, but not be limited to, all of the
138 following matters:
139 a. The transfer of ownership of health care facilities,
140 health care services, real property, and other tangible or
Page 5

health care services, real property, and other tangible or
SB352 INTRODUCED
141 intangible assets to the new authority.
142 b. Required changes in corporate ownership or
143 governance of affected health care facilities or health care
144 services to be delivered by the new authority, including
145 amendment, reincorporation, or dissolution of public hospital
146 corporations that are agents or instrumentalities of, or which
147 share executives, directors, employees, contractors, or
148 facilities with, the existing authority.
149 c. With respect to outstanding liabilities of the
150 existing authority, including, but not limited to, indentures,
151 securities, coupon payments, or loans, the assumption by the
152 new authority of an equitable proportion of outstanding
153 liabilities, including periodic debt service, that reflects
154 the benefit conferred on health care infrastructure in the
155 service area of the new authority by any of the obligations.
156 d. With respect to income of the existing authority
157 from revenue sources, including, but not limited to, loan
158 proceeds, securities, federal, state, or private grants,
159 revenue streams from the state and authorizing subdivisions
160 designated to the existing authority in the form of proceeds
161 from any property tax, privilege tax, license, or other fees,
162 allocation to the new authority of an equitable proportion of
163 the income that reflects the intent or purpose of any of the
164 revenue as applicable to benefit health care delivery or
165 infrastructure in the service area of the new authority.
166 e. Distribution to, or sharing between, the two
167 authorities of outstanding contractual obligations relating to
168 health care delivery, including physician or other licensed
Page 6

health care delivery, including physician or other licensed
