197 (5) The plan as finalized shall be a contract that is
198 enforceable by either authority, any authorizing subdivision
199 of either authority, or any affected health care facility, by
200 any remedy available at law or equity in the court of probate
201 with jurisdiction over the plan as provided in subdivision
202 (b)(3).
203 (d)(1) At any time during the development of the plan
204 required by subsection (c), any matter in controversy or
205 requiring settlement may be referred by the judge of probate
206 to arbitration by settlement upon:
207 a. Petition filed by the board of either authority, an
208 authorizing subdivision of either authority, or an affected
209 health care facility; or
210 b. Upon order entered, sua sponte, by the judge of
211 probate.
212 (2) The judge of probate shall appoint by order a
213 disinterested arbitrator who has experience in the resolution
214 of disputes that involve the acquisition, divestiture, or
215 dissolution of business or nonprofit entities, assets, and
216 obligations.
217 (3) The order required in subdivision (2) shall specify
218 the matters in controversy for resolution.
219 (4)a. The arbitration proceedings shall be conducted in
220 accordance with the Guidelines for Arbitration Proceedings in
221 Alabama published by the Alabama Supreme Court Commission on
222 Dispute Resolution.
223 b. The judge of probate may enter any order concerning
224 the conduct of the arbitration, on motion of one of the
Page 8

the conduct of the arbitration, on motion of one of the
SB352 INTRODUCED
225 parties in paragraph (1)a. or the arbitrator, or sua sponte,
226 relating to enforcement of any order of the arbitrator,
227 including a finding of civil contempt or appropriate
228 injunctive relief.
229 (5) The arbitrator shall issue a written award that
230 resolves the matters referred for arbitration, which shall be
231 distributed to the negotiating boards. The arbitrator shall
232 submit the written award to the judge of probate no more 10
233 days from issuance. The judge of probate may do any of the
234 following no less than 10 days after submission by the
235 arbitrator:
236 a. Adopt and enter the award as an order of the court.
237 b. Set aside the award in whole or in part, and refer
238 the matters in dispute to the same arbitrator with
239 instructions or to a different arbitrator.
240 c. Schedule a hearing no more than 30 days from the
241 filing of an objection to the award by one of the negotiating
242 boards, which objection shall be filed with the judge of
243 probate no more than 10 days from the arbitrator's issuance of
244 the award.
245 (6) If a hearing is conducted pursuant to paragraph
246 (5)c., the judge of probate shall enter an order no more than
247 10 days after the hearing which:
248 a. Adopts and enters the award as an order of the
249 court, to include any modification that the judge of probate
250 deems equitable or appropriate; or
251 b. Sets aside the award in whole or in part, and refers
252 the matters in dispute to the same arbitrator with
Page 9

the matters in dispute to the same arbitrator with
